get.summary: Version Request; This is a simple request that returns the version of the API.
get.description: Will return the API version, (e.g. '1.0.0 -- Initial version').

get.summary: Data Request; This is the request that returns the data to build the charts.
get.description: This is the request that returns the data to build the charts. Here you will be able to select the parameters to build different types of charts (pie chart, data grid, line chart, KPI, etc...), filter your data, apply different time ranges or choose from one of the different metrics available.

parameters.name: system_code
parameters.description: System code of the account that you want to retrieve data from

parameters.name: fromDate
parameters.description: Indicates the initial date of the query. It accepts YYYY-MM-DD or YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm:ss formats as well as a 'long' timestamp. It also accepts the next predefined values: 'last5minutes', 'last10minutes', 'lasthour', 'last3hours', 'last6hours', 'yesterday', 'today'. This end point allows you to query for metrics from any time period

parameters.name: toDate
parameters.description: Indicates the final date of the query. It accepts YYYY-MM-DD or YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm:ss formats as well as a 'long' timestamp. If one of the predefined values in fromDate is selected, toDate should not be filled up

parameters.name: filter
parameters.description: In this field can be setted an indefinite number of filters. In all cases the structure must follow the next structure: &filter=filtername:{dimesion1:value1,value2},{dimension2:value3,value4}. If you want more information, there is a section below that explains how to create complex filters

parameters.name: granularity
parameters.description: Time granularity in which the data points are going to be returned. The available values are: 'minute', 'hour', 'day', 'week', 'month', 'quarter', 'year'

parameters.name: type
parameters.description: Type of data to filter, 'ALL', 'VOD', 'LIVE'. Can be used individually or with any combination (comma-separated)

parameters.name: timezone
parameters.description: The time zone to apply in the dates queries. See table of Timezone Codes for valid entries

parameters.name: operation
parameters.description: The type of operation to apply. Three operation types: Join: Allows aggregate different series into one. For example, this operation can aggregate values corresponding of Mediterranean countries into one serie Reducejoin: This option performs a join operation and deletes the temporal dimension in the aggregation, so the final result will be the KPI of the aggregation Reducedisjoin: Perform reduce operation and splits the results into the passed groupBy values

parameters.name: metrics
parameters.description: Selection of the metric that will be computed. If you want to know more about the different kind of metrics, please follow this link

parameters.name: groupBy
parameters.description: Selector of the dimension where the different entities will be grouped by. As an example, if the dimension selected is Country, all the different entities; EEUU, Canada, Spain… will be returned

parameters.name: orderBy
parameters.description: This determines which order will follow the response. For example, if Views is selected, the entities will be ordered by the number of views

parameters.name: limit
parameters.description: Maximum number of results returned

parameters.name: orderDirection
parameters.description: This parameter determines if the order is ascendent or descendent

parameters.name: kpiGroup
parameters.description: By selecting one of the predefined kpi groups, you will see the data of the system selected compared to the data of the group

parameters.name: outFile
parameters.description: True or False to download the data or not

parameters.name: outFilename
parameters.description: Name of the file that will be downloaded

parameters.name: csvFormat
parameters.description: If True, the response is formatted as a csv, if False, the response is formatted as a JSON

parameters.name: dateToken
parameters.description: Token that determines the duration of the request

parameters.name: token
parameters.description: Timed token to expire requests. Please, there is a section below that explains how to generate tokens

get.summary: Events Request; These are the calls that return the events of a view.
get.description: These are the calls that return the information related with the events of a given media session. A view, determined by a token, can have different events as Join Time, Buffers...

parameters.name: system_code
parameters.description: System code of the account that you want to retrieve data from

parameters.name: filter
parameters.description: Valid token of a specific view to obtain the events of this session. e.g. Token:{token:U_13_7kthuw4s5zy2bo76}

parameters.name: fromDate
parameters.description: Indicates the initial date of the query. It accepts YYYY-MM-DD or YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm:ss formats as well as a 'long' timestamp. It also accepts the next predefined values: 'last5minutes', 'last10minutes', 'lasthour', 'last3hours', 'last6hours', 'yesterday', 'today'. This end point allows you to query for metrics from any time period

get.summary: Switching_events Request; These are the calls that return all the switches of a view.
get.description: These are the calls that return information related with any switches of a given media session. From here you can see, from an specific session, all the different kind of switches: Renditions, CDNs, Title, ISP and Custom Dimensions
